@node Introduction, TeXdraw commands, Top, Top
@chapter Introduction

@TeX{} is a powerful typesetting program written by D. Knuth.  It allows
for complex text layouts but by itself lacks a general graphics
capability.  However, when coupled with an appropriate printing program,
external graphics files can be inserted into the printed document.  In
this mode, @TeX{} is instructed to leave space for a drawing.  The
drawing is inserted at print time by the print program.  The @TeX{}draw
macros generate the external graphics file from within @TeX{} and
generate the instructions to the the print program to position the
graphics at the appropriate position on the page.  In this way,
@TeX{}draw produces drawings from @emph{within} @TeX{}.

@TeX{}draw consists of a set of @TeX{} macros that create line drawings
and other figures.  The drawing primitives include solid lines,
patterned lines, Bezier curves, circles and arrows.  Other commands
allow for the filling of a region with a gray level.  The drawing
commands generate PostScript code.  This limits @TeX{}draw to systems
which use PostScript printers.  @TeX{}draw also provides commands to
position @TeX{} text, including mathematics, on the drawing.  The final
drawing, with text and graphics, can be positioned on the page like any
other @TeX{} box.

@TeX{}draw generates an intermediate PostScript file for the drawing
commands.  This file is included in the final printout by invoking the
@code{\special} command provided by @TeX{}.  The present version of
@TeX{}draw uses the @code{\special} syntax recognized by the program
@file{dvips} by Tom Rokicki.  The program @file{dvips} is used to
process the device independent (dvi) output file produced by @TeX{}.
The program @file{dvips} combines the PostScript drawing commands from
the intermediate PostScript file and the text positioning information
from the dvi file into a single PostScript file which can be printed on
a PostScript printer.  The program @file{dvips} also automatically
scales the PostScript figure to compensate for changes to the @TeX{}
magnification, so that @TeX{} text and the PostScript graphics remain
aligned.  The structure of @TeX{}draw is such that only minor changes
need be made to allow it to be used with other dvi to PostScript drivers
that allow for the inclusion of PostScript files, at least at nominal
magnification.

The basic @TeX{}draw macros provide only simple drawing commands.
However, @TeX{}draw provides a drawing segment environment which allows
parameter changes and coordinate scaling changes to be kept local to the
drawing segment.  This facility, together with @TeX{}'s macro
capabilities allows one to modularize drawing units and extend
@TeX{}draw by building more complex graphics entities from simpler
elements.  New user commands can be defined using the tools used to
construct the basic @TeX{}draw commands.

