@node History, Distribution, , Introduction
@section History
@cindex history of @TeX{}draw
@cindex predecessors to @TeX{}draw

The @TeX{}draw macros have evolved from the @TeX{}graph macros, written
by Michael Ferguson at INRS-Telecommunications, University of Quebec.
In its first incarnation, @TeX{}graph generated output for a QMS (QUIC
graphics language) laser printer.  A later version wrote PostScript
output directly to the dvi file for subsequent printing by a modified
version of the @file{dvialw} dvi to PostScript driver.

The functional interface for @TeX{}draw is largely based on @TeX{}graph.
However, @TeX{}draw writes PostScript commands to an intermediate file.
This file is a PostScript file which can be printed on its own, although
the position of the drawing may be offset with respect to the the
printed page.  The intermediate file is printed as part of the document,
correctly positioned using the @code{\special} command mechanism.

